---
layout: post
title: "Solar Radiation and Propellor Anemometers- Wind/Solar Coupling"
date: 2015-04-07T09:41:02-07:00
---

Detecting spikes in solar radiation and wind proves difficult because there is a coupling effect between air temperatures, solar radiation, and wind speed that I did not initially expect.

1. Solar radiation spikes always occur between 10:00 and 14:00
2. Solar radiation spikes always occur during the summer
3. Wind spikes also always occur "during the day" (although not necessarily as constrained)
4. Wind spikes can occur at any time of year
5. Temperature spikes can occur just about any time (but many are instrument errors)

(Regarding temperatures, the four-sigma test has been implemented in our system and does an "okay" job of flagging air temperatures. While it does find the great outliers, it has trouble with times which are within the boundaries of the sigmas, but are still clearly problematic. For example, just below zero values in August on CENMET during a logger change.)

Back to solar, I set a limit of 900 W/m2 to flag on CENMET between the months of May and October (since no values in other months were exceptional) and between the hours of 7 am and 17:00. This limit generates slightly too many flags for comfort, although it represents the 95% of possible solar radiation available on a curved earth, and slightly more than should be possible at our latitude.

Here the problem of coupling is evident. During the warm day we have higher windspeeds and also higher temperatures and higher radiation maximums. Additionally, 900 simply isn't extreme enough to show spikes. We can zoom in on any of these periods and see that they are well within the "trend" of the instrument.

CENMET, not unfortunately, didn't have too many extreme values. However, we know from other analyses that VANMET generally has a lot of bad values. Taking the same time period on VANMET with both a 900 and a 1060 limit (highest possible on earth due to atmosphere) still generated FAR too many values. Although they should all be flagged, they do not tell us anything about what is going awry. Observe the 2012 summer at VANMET:

This doesn't look lke much offhand, but if one zooms into the chart, an interesting fact is that the high solar values occur at exactly the same time every single day. Again, this could be due to the fact that every day it is simply warmest between 11 am and 1 pm. An interesting fact to note is that there is a tremendous gap in the propellor anemometer data during that may, and the problems appear to have started just after this. There are less than half as many problems in the historical data prior to this time than there are following it (although, the data was at a lesser resolution).

I then bumped the threshold to flag up to 1200, and looked only for May-August on VANMET. This is when a few interesting features can be seen.

Although this threshold is higher, when we zoom in to say, June 15 -20, it is evident that the times during which VANMET is registering extreme values, so is CENMET! Yes, the values on VANMET are > 300 W/ms2 higher, but they are at the exact same times.

Here's some features we detect:

* extreme values of solar radiation are coupled across sites
* extreme values of solar radiation appear to occur right before the peak temperature of the day
* extreme values of solar radiation seem de-coupled from wind. They occur during the same part of the day when wind is blowing strongly, but do not seem to be affected by it. Note that I purposefully used the non-aspirated shields in this part of the analysis so that if there were a temperature anomaly, I might sense it.

Given the output from these two sites, my suggestion might be that these extreme values like we see on VANMET get flagged in the historical data, and in the future, the net radiometer used to control for these spikes. Looking across the shortwave ins and pyranometer values on CENMET, VANMET, and PRIMET should offer guidance to how to control these bad values.
